  <title translate="true">Menus and Toolbars</title>
  <body>
    <header>
      <para styleclass="Heading1"><text styleclass="Heading1" translate="true">Menus and Toolbars</text></para>
    </header>
    <para styleclass="Normal"><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true">More often, commands are initiated from menus and toolbars. The </text><text styleclass="Program Feature" translate="true">View Composer</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true"> includes a </text><text styleclass="Program Feature" translate="true">Menu Composer</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true"> to help with the creation of menu bars and context menus. This is accessible from within the </text><text styleclass="Menu Command" translate="true">Modify/Menu Bar</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true"> or </text><text styleclass="Menu Command" translate="true">Modify/Context Menu</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true"> pulldowns but it is beyond the scope of this tutorial to go into the details of menu building. You should find the </text><text styleclass="Program Feature" translate="true">Menu Composer</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true"> fairly intuitive to use if you want to add, say, a </text><text styleclass="Menu Command" translate="true">Transaction</text><text styleclass="Normal" translate="true"> menu to the menu bar of the shell. Such a menu could be used to send the same commands as the push buttons thus giving the user a choice of how to use the interface.</text></para>
  </body>
